# 🔹 What is Dynamic Programming (DP)?

Dynamic Programming (DP) is an algorithmic technique used to solve problems by:

* Breaking them into **overlapping subproblems**
* Solving each subproblem **only once**
* Storing the result to avoid recomputation

📌 **Idea:**

> "Solve once, store forever, reuse whenever needed."

---

# 🔹 When to Use Dynamic Programming?

A problem is suitable for DP if it satisfies:

### 1️⃣ Optimal Substructure

The optimal solution can be built from optimal solutions of smaller subproblems.

---

### 2️⃣ Overlapping Subproblems

The same subproblems are solved repeatedly.

Example:

Fibonacci

```text
F(5)
├── F(4)
│   ├── F(3)
│   └── F(2)
└── F(3)
```

Notice:

**F(3)** is computed twice.

DP stores it after the first computation.

---

# 🔹 Dynamic Programming vs Recursion

| Recursion              | Dynamic Programming     |
| ---------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Recomputes subproblems | Stores results          |
| Slower                 | Faster                  |
| Higher time complexity | Reduced time complexity |
| Less memory            | More memory             |

---

# 🔹 Memoization (Top-Down DP)

Memoization uses:

✅ Recursion

* Storage (cache/array)

Whenever a subproblem is solved:

Store the answer.

If encountered again:

Return stored value.

---

### Fibonacci Example

Without DP

```text
F(5)
├──F(4)
│ ├──F(3)
│ └──F(2)
└──F(3)
```

Repeated work.

---

With Memoization

Each Fibonacci value is computed only once.

---

## Complexity

Time:

[
O(n)
]

Space:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Tabulation (Bottom-Up DP)

Starts from the smallest subproblem.

Builds solutions iteratively.

---

Example:

```text
dp[0]=0

dp[1]=1

dp[2]=1

dp[3]=2

dp[4]=3

dp[5]=5
```

---

### Complexity

Time:

[
O(n)
]

Space:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Memoization vs Tabulation

| Memoization          | Tabulation         |
| -------------------- | ------------------ |
| Top-down             | Bottom-up          |
| Uses recursion       | Uses iteration     |
| Easier to write      | Usually faster     |
| Uses recursion stack | No recursion stack |

